            </TextBlock.RenderTransform><Run Text="Ideal Op Amp"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="An Op amp has infinite differential-voltage gain, infinite input resistance and zero output resistance. Vout = gain (v1-v2). If the gain of the Op-amp of large enough the input port of the op-amp becomes a null port when negative feedback is applied.   Non linear characteristics include: "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* finite differential input impedance  and a non-zero  output resistance "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* common mode input resistance, Vos = input offset voltage, "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Ios = input offset current which is necessary to make the output voltage"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="zero if the op-amp is driven by two identical sources, Ios=Ib1-Ib2, which for MOSFETs is approximately zero and CMMR.   The power supply rejection ratio (PSRR)  is  = change in Vdd/ change in Vout *open loop gain."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Can also be written as ratio of the differential gain to the gain from the power supply ripple to the output  with the Vin=0.When selecting or designing Op-amp the following requirements  need to"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="be evaluated for  a supply voltage of +/-2.5v."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Gain "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Gain bandwidth ."/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Settling time"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Slew rat"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Input common mode range ,ICMR"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Common mode rejection ratio, CMRR"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Power supply rejection ratio ,PSRR"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Output voltage swing"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Offset"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Noise"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="* Layout area"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="The stability of  an op-amp is characterized by it's phase margin. With large"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="capacitive loads several compensation procedures exist to achieve a good"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="phase margin. Miller compensation is one example."/></TextBlock>
